<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-278-178  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 278 178.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Feb 20 1989 v3 n8 p6(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Panel wants suspect-tracking system scuttled.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Casatelli, Christine.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A panel of computer and privacy experts has recommended that asystem to use a computer database to track criminal suspects notbe developed.andP;  The system, proposed by the FBI, would maintaininformation on-line and connect to other civil data bases.andP;  Areport by computer and privacy experts maintains that it would bedifficult to maintain system security and to verify the accuracyof information kept on the system.andP;  Since the system would includeinformation on people suspected of criminal activity, it couldeasily become a surveillance network, and as such might violatecivil rights.andP;  The system was to be part of a redesign of theFBI's National Crime Information Center, which stores 20 millionrecords and responds to 750,000 inquiries each day from lawenforcement officials nationwide.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationUnited States. National Crime Information CenterSecurityData Bases.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>